For example, the input could be "S T A B U" all on one line, or split into multiple lines. But in C, scanf with %s will read until whitespace, so even if the input is split into lines, it should read correctly. So in C:

char S[100], T[100], U[100];
int A, B;

scanf("%s %s % d % d %s", S, T, &A, &B, U); Wait, but the order is S, T, A, B, U. So the input is S and T first, then A and B, then U. So the scanf format string should be "%s %s % d % d %s". Yes. So that's how we read them. Then compare U with S and T using strcmp. If strcmp(U, S) == 0, then A--. Similarly for T.

Then print A and B.

So putting it all together. But need to handle the includes:

#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

Then the main function:

int main() {
    char S[100], T[100], U[100];
    int A, B;

    // Read the inputs. Assuming the input is correct. scanf("%s %s %d % d %s", S, T, &A, &B, U);

    if (strcmp(U, S) == 0) {
        A--;
    } if (strcmp(U, T) == 0) {
        B--;
    }

    printf("%d %d\n", A, B);
    return 0;
}

